  "text": "Frankincense and myrrh are gum resins obtained from the genera Boswellia and Commiphora, respectively. Modern pharmacological research has revealed that essential oils are the primary effective components in frankincense and myrrh oil that exhibit a broad spectrum of biological activities, principally antimicrobial, anti-inflammatory, and antitumor activities. As with other essential oils, the instability and poor water solubility result in poor oral bioavailability, which limits its clinical application. The components of frankincense and myrrh oil are very sensitive to light, air, and high temperature, and they stimulate the gastrointestinal tract, making these oils unsuitable for oral administration. A recent study has reported the successful preparation of solid lipid nanoparticles for the oral delivery of frankincense and myrrh essential oils [CITATION_1] .",
